,Recommended,244770,13627706,"Posted: 26 December, 2014",all,American Vro,"My first StarMade Experience:1st-2nd hours:I get on the server (redshift). I am so damn overwhelmed by the cool spawn and spaceships docked there. I have no idea of what to do, so I request help from a fellow player. One thing leads to another, and I am now in this guy's faction. its just the guy, his friend, and me. He surprisingly has about six ships, 2 for mining, one with a jump drive, a few fighters, and some other huge ship with unknown purpose,also a space station orbiting a terraformed planet. Guy teaches me the basics, and then logs off. You can not blame me for wanting to try out the stuff. First I try building my own ship, a core, a power supply and a thruster, and I realize the ship is simple and fast. I land on the planet. I forget to press shift. ship flies off even with me getting out of it. I'm stranded in the planet. SHEEEEIIIIT. I start mining blocks, and build a pilar trying to reach the space station. I am successful, and get back on.3rd Hour:I now am familiar with the basic controls of the game (I took a while to get used to the controls of this one). I am curious, so I decide to take the warpship for a spin. The jumpdrive jumps about 8 sectors per jump. I start charging and jumping all over the universe,the setting is relaxed, I'm listening to some slow trance,and I am actually having a lot of fun exploring. Suddenly I see another station. ""I should dock there"" I thought. As I arrive near the foreign station my systems begin to fail, and I start getting blasted. I mean BLASTED by lazers and projectiles of all sorts. The ship is dead. THE SHIP IS ♥♥♥♥ING DEAD!!! THE GUY IS GONNA KILL ME!!!!!! How would I look him in the eyes, the one person who helped me out, who took me under his wing, I was ashamed. I managed to find my way back to my faction's station, and about half hour later the faction leader who took me in logged on. oshitoshitoshitoshitosheeit. First thing he asks me: ""hey man, have you seen the jumpship, you know the one that looks kind of like a satellite?"" ""Y-yes I s-s-aw s-someone stealing it"". He looked at me, then he kicked me out of the faction, and blew me back to spawn.10/10 would steal a jumpship and lie about it again"
76561198099635950,Recommended,244770,14334095,"Posted: 4 February, 2015",all,Tommy Potato,"On my daily game browsing, I was looking for anything interesting. I came across this game. This is one of the coolest games I have ever played. Some people say this is a Space Engineers clone...it is not. And I am sure (Idk who or why) someone has called this a Minecraft clone...GOD no. (It's in space, come on now.) I will break this up into different sections, with a TL;DR at the end, as well as a section for those who read the whole thing! Thank you.ONE MORE THING: The demo unlocks the whole game for free. The developer said it will stay that way until it goes out of early access, and that buying it is mainly just to support development.Why it is awesome:1. Customization. You can build any kind of ship you want. A ship for transporting things, a ship for mining, a fighter, a massive battle ship, a mining ship with salvage beams (Those are beams that mine for you. SO you shoot at something, it being an ore, rock, or even parts of another ship or station) or any combination of all. (This is not all, of course)2. Fighting. The fighting is incredible and fun, and fast paced action. It is like a Star Wars battle. You can have your fleet of 20 ships versus another player's fleet of 20 ships or against Space Pirates, or in single player, you versus a bunch of pirates (Idk yet if you can have computer controlled fighting allies in singleplayer) The complex weapons systems are for a whole other part of the review.3. The complex weapons systems. There is the basic cannons, lasers, and missiles, and they are fun and damaging. You can make the cannons and any other weapon touch each other to make 1 very damaging weapon, or you can space them out to have many of that weapon firing at once. Here is where it gets complex. You can combine weapons. *SPOILER HERE* So you can combine the cannon and the missile to make a shotgun like weapon on your ship. *SPOILER END* Cool right? And there are over 80 combinations (so I have read). So lots of fun to be had with weapons. (And don't be afraid to stack them up a ton. If you have the weapons available, and the power available, make some crazy weapons systems.)4. NPCs. This is where Space Engineers is lacking so far, but will have them in the future. There are, like I said, Space Pirates. They have killed me many times. But if you have the power and the numbers, fight them back and steal from them and you shall be granted rich reward...so I assume. There are also NPCs at some shops.5. Shops. You can go to a shop and buy anything in the game. You need a lot of money for many things, but you can get a lot of money fairly easy with the right knowledge of what is really valuable, like ores and glass. (More fun with shops later in the review)6 Space Stations. You can do a lot of the same stuff with stations that you can do with ships. I am not sure what it has weapons wise, but I am sure there are good things with that. I know there are turrets. Automated turrets and controllable I think. Very customizable. To make a space station though, you need 1,000,000 credits. Which tbh, isn't that bad. I saw one guy get like 2 million credits from selling a bunch of salvaged (collected) glass. And with a faction you can claim a station as yours and make it invulnerable to damage and stealing. It also makes any docked ships invulnerable too. So griefers aren't a problem with this HAHA!7. Factions. You can make a faction and build on faction points with players to join it (Idk if npcs can join or not), taking over sectors and systems, defeating enemies, and so on. With a faction you can claim a space station and make it invulnerable to damage and stealing. And you can claim a whole system as your territory. Again, there are 128 x 128 x 128 (I think) sectors in a system, so that is a TON of space as yours. With a faction, you can also make your own shops! You can price items how you want, decide what is on your market, and sell things to other players, and maybe even npcs. (You may not need a faction, you may only need a space station to make a shop. I can't remember) And with a faction you can keep growing your territory until you take over everything MUAHAHAHAHAHHAHA! (Not even kidding though)8. Build mode/Advanced build mode. Who doesn't love a good build mode for easy ship/station construction? With regular build mode you can do all the basic stuff like placing/deleting blocks, flying, sped up flying, connecting blocks and groups, and all that stuff. With advanced build mode, you can use symmetry (For precise building), copy/pasting/saving pieces of ships or stations as templates, mass building with placing up to 10 blocks in every axis at a time (So you can build a 10 x 10 x 10 cube with one click), rotating blocks, and a few other things. So very fun and easy to use. Makes for easy building of a massive ship.9. Jump drives/Warp gates. *SPOILER HERE* The jump drives and warp gates are a great way to get around fast, but you need alot of power. With a jump drive, you can ""jump"" up to 8 sectors away. With warp gates, (I think) you can warp up to 128 sectors away. So very convenient.10. Asteroids, planets, stars, stations. These are all procedurally generated. Very cool.Now, for the cons. However, some of these are personal opinions and may not matter to you.1. *PERSONAL OPINION* This game has blocks, not voxels. Sometimes I prefer voxels instead of blocks because realistic smooth surface terrain is cool, but it is not a big deal, this game is still great.2. Memory issues. I have noticed a lot of people having memory issues where it gets very laggy and a message pops up in game and says you are running low on memory, and to increase the max and min memory in the launcher, you can edit the memory settings like it says, but some people still get the issue. I have fixed it for the most part, but some people can't. Maybe the devs will fix this or optimize it.Other than these, that's all I got for the cons. Great right? lolNow, this section is WHY it is NOT a clone of Space Engineers.1. It is blocks, not voxels.2. It has planets, stars (Stars that you can actually go to and burn up and die, not just the background sun), sectors, systems, and galaxies.3. It ALREADY has NPCs, I know SE will have them, but this game already does.4. It has customizable weapons and complex combination systems.5. It has more than just 1 type of metal block. Just saying lol.6. Build mode/advanced build mode.7. More content with factions (SO FAR).*Don't get me wrong, I still love and play Space Engineers, but I wanted to clear this up for people who think this is a clone because it most certainly is not**ONE MORE THING BEFORE WE WRAP THIS UP* It is still early access (For those who don't know what that means), it is still being developed, it will change, get worse, get fixed, get better, and maybe even become something different.*TL;DR*Now, for the people who didn't feel like reading all of that, here is a basic summary:It is an incredibly fun game with many unique features, and very few bugs that I have noticed. Not many cons at all, and I suggest this to any person. STILL early access so things will change, get worse, get fixed, get better and maybe even become something different. NOT a clone of Space Engineers. (I covered that in the above section)*FOR THOSE WHO READ THE WHOLE THING*Thanks for taking the time to read and I hope you found this helpful. :)"
76561198103394373,Recommended,244770,13627210,"Posted: 26 December, 2014",all,Felldrake,"If you ever wanted to play Eve Online, but did not want to spend years of your life mining for other players to build big ships. If you ever looked at the sky while playing Minecraft and said ""I want more.."". If you ever wanted to go where no man has gone before, create a galactic Empire more vast that the Imperium of Man, or create an intersteller Jihad that claims more worlds than the war started by Paul Atredies, then THIS is the game for you."
,Recommended,244770,13252172,"Posted: 6 December, 2014",all,bunpro,"After creating ""La Scrubs"" faction with a friend, we built a ship with a hyper-drive to fly to a randomly generated quadrant of the galaxy, found and took over a space station then took apart our old ship, attatched the hyper-drive to the space station, and used the newly adapted space-ship-station to fly into a partially loaded planet. The planet, which had not loaded in properly, now had a gigantic space station sticking out of it! Unfortunately the planet's core is a stationary object, so we couldn't use the hyper-drive to fly the space-ship-station-planet into a moon. :("
,Not Recommended,244770,19538498,"Posted: 6 December, 2015",all,Asvarduil,"Once upon a time...no, wait, never mind.  I'm still bulding the U.S.S Defiant.StarMadeis a block-buildy gameIn Space!The best way to explain it to people is, to start by imagining MineCraft.  Now, take your awesome castle, and put thrusters and guns on it.  That's StarMade...only, it's notquiteas engaging, even about seven months after my original review.Some changes have happened, including a price hike to $14.99.  Thus, I'm taking the extra hours I've played in the intervening months into account, and doing a re-review.  Has it improved?  Well...you will see.What WorksFirst, the visuals have improved greatly from my prior review, and the game overall looks pretty nice.  You can build some neat ships and stations.  The Pentas/Tetras/Corners allow for somewhat blocky re-builds of your favorite Sci-Fi ships, or your own custom creations.  Some recent texture updates from the developers have made good ships look even better!Performance is also improved to the point where the game is at least playable on medium-grade machines.  This was a critical problem for me in my previous review, but the developers deserve credit for working to make the game behave more efficiently.  Good job there!The UI has improved a lot in seven months too.  There are some issues with resizing individual windows, but the game is easily understandable via the UI, and gives you most of the tools you need to build ships, which is the game's primary mechanic.  The secondary mechanic, shooting stuff with your ship, is also well-accounted for, with shield, structural HP, and armor HP being presented well.  There are some placeholders about, as this game is still in development, but progress is being made.  I'm sure seven months in the future, the UI will be a lot better than it already is, and I look forward to that.What Doesn't WorkBefore I get to anything heavy, I have to talk about the crafting system.  The crafting system is OK in a survival setting, and some much-needed tuning has happened...but ultimately, to make a decent ship, you needa lotof blocks, because in this game, bigger ship = better.  There's additional problems with that that we will get to, but the crafting system as it stands actually hampers the process of doing the main thing that you should be doing in a game about building starships:actually building starships.To solve this, the crafting UI and system needs a pretty massive interface revamp, and some thought should be taken to all the 'wasted' blocks about, things like plantlife that could be leveraged to make more interesting builds.  It's as if the developers started off by copying MineCraft, then at some point decided, ""oh yeah, the point of this game is to make ships!""Next, there's a problem with how the shipbuilding mechanics in this game are balanced, specifically:anyship you make is a fighter.  You don't need crews to tend to large ships.  You just need your ship to be bigger than an enemy's, because a bigger ship fits more systems in it, and systems are what cause you to win fights, eat asteroids or planets, or whatever.  The recent Cargo system that was released yesterday will help prevent planet-eating miners from being quite as big of a problem as they were prior to this (good luck fitting a planet in your cargo holds), but those of you wondering whether or not to buy into this game should know that, especially in multiplayer, the shipbuilding mechanic is unfairly weighted towards building big ships; smaller ships are thus forced out of niches that are realistic, such as bombers/interceptors.As big of problems as those points are, there was one critical problem in my prior review, thatthere's nothing really to do, no reason to actually build a ship.This one, big, critical, overarching problem persists to this day, and it makes the entire game, all the well-crafted bits,completely pointless.There are some feeble attempts to remedy this - specifically a ""race gate"" minigame setup was added to the game in a more recent release.The reason I say, ""there is nothing to do in StarMade"", is tied more specifically to two things.In Single-Player, there's really nothing to explore.  StarMade randomly generates universes, but other than finding slightly different ores on planets, you may as well not bother.  There are randomly generated space stations too, but do they reward anything?  Not really, unless you salvage the station.  In StarMade, you'll soon discover one thing: due to how the Crafting system works (above),it's generally better to avoid conflict altogether, or your lovingly-crafted spaceship will cease to be, and you will have to grind out a new ship.In Multi-Player, it gets worse.  The Faction system in StarMade is...well, a faction system.  Ideally, players pool their resources to create fleets, stations, and stuff, thus providing a natural objective for PvP.  Sounds great, right?  Unfortunately, due to not designing the Faction system to account for humanity's darker impulses, the only way to secure anything you own, is to create a one-man faction, and set a planet or space station as the home base...rendering the systems inoperable by non-guildmembers, and storage secure.  In this way, your stuff is safe from griefing, and as far as I can tell, it's the way the game is designed to be played.  That's well and good...except that's not really the point of a Faction, now is it?.The way I suggest for the developers to fix StarMade's pointlessness is two-fold.First, there needs to be a meaningful progression that doesn't come out of your workbenches.  You should have to explore, and give exploration some meaning besides ""where are the ores?""  If you want to create a civilian ship, ask yourself: why create a civilian ship?  Trade, mining, and ferrying come to mind.  Those are some great candidates for randomized quests that can be rewarded with blocks, money, or useful ship blueprints.  For that matter -make the premade ships not suck so much!Existing ships can serve a great purpose - teaching new players the nuances of StarMade's shipbuilding mechanics.  In this way, players build better, interesting ships, which forges a stronger community and makes PvP more reasonable as an implicit objective.Next,you have to fix factions.  Single-player factions destroy the fun of multiplayer in this game.  My suggestion is for players to have 'personal home' blocks that can be used to secure a personal space on a station or planet against anyone who's not them; all chests/cargo areas in that are similarly preserved.  Similarly, creating a faction should require a party of at least two people.  The home-base constraint can still apply, and should.   The game needs better in-faction control to help Factions defend against spies and ne'erdowells.As long as players make single-person factions, your multiplayer is broken.You're just putting single-player on a multi-player server.The TL;DRI have a love-hate relationship with this game.  On the one hand, Ireally dolike building starships.  On the other, this game is less of a ""game"" in the ""you can win or lose"" sense, and more of a starship building simulator.  The price of the game was increased to $14.99 from $9.99...I see nothing that justifies this price hike.As a result, I emphaticallydo notrecommend purchasing StarMade.This game will be fun, possibly for weeks, until you begin to see the legion of flaws and the fact that this game is a simulator.  $14.99 is how muchcompletedindie games cost on Steam; this game is neither completed, nor sufficiently fun enough to bear that price tag."
,Not Recommended,244770,29426996,Posted: 22 January,all,RedAlert_007,"""Starmade has become the exact thing that early access is infamous for. Good luck marketing your game 1-2 years down the line when it has a 6 year reputation of being a buggy broken mess.Go play avorion, take a look at how those build tools feel. Go spend a few hours in empyrion, see how the survival mechanics work. Go play starpoint gemini warlords, see how well fleet mechanics work. There is no defending Starmade when you compare it to games that work.""-Comr4de, StarMade Veteran and former member of StarMade's ""Council of Intergalactic Representatives""The simple observation that a lot of white knights/fanboys are roaming this games reviews and mass disliking any review that speaks bad of this game speaks volumes about the community of this game.UPDATE 1: I have noted that a lot of the usual fanboys of this game are commenting on bad reviews claiming they are invalid because they amount to ""Its bad"" yet the very same players are upvoting and praising reviews that simply amount to ""Its good""UPDATE 2: On May 16, 2017 the developers have announced they will be completely rewriting the building system in ships in a system they call ""Ship Systems 2.0"" I feel this to be a testemony to the incompetance of the developers of this game, 6 years of development and they decide to completely change the gamenowof all times? Worth noting that the devs in charge of NPC assets had not even finished the NPC faction stations using the current system when this was announced. Now the developers will need to completely remake every single NPC and AI asset, which they have demonstrated their inability to do so in the past from their regular streams. You would think Schine would use systems 2.0 as an oppurtunity to make a new engine that could handle the scale of building it is advertised at, but apparently not.UPDATE 3: On July 5, 2017 yet another veteran StarMade player and former StarMade Council member Comr4de has quit StarMade and declared he would no longer support this games development (if you can even call it a game at this point) I wonder who is next?Comr4de has written up an excellent post that summarised the current state of the game on StarMadeDock, you can find said post here:https://starmadedock.net/threads/devblog-27th-june-2017.29185/page-2#post-343544As for the game itself:Pros:Easily the best building system in any voxel based game I have seen recentlyHaving now played Avorion I can no longer stand by this statement, the building system in Avorion is essentialy a better version of StarMade's building systemMore voxel shapes for you to chose from and the ability to change the dimensions of said shapes (in StarMade every shape is the same size and the only way to make a ""bigger wedge"" is to place multiple wedges) combined with the ability to disable the snap grid and completely freebuild is something that StarMade's building system cannot compare too.The possibilities presented by StarMades logic system are endlessCons:PvP is a mess, extreme weapon and combat system inbalance combined with the idea that bigger ships will always win make for unfun experience.The engine created by Schine cannot handle combat on any scale unless the server is running on top of the line hardware that most server owners do not have the budget to maintain, especialy considering there are not enough players left in the game to run a server off donations.PvE is practicaly nonexistant, the NPC update did take a step in the right direction but PvE is pretty much going to pirate stations and AFK farming them with logic activated missile+missile weapons. Also worth mentioning that the NPC update has been a responsible factor in causing server wide instability on servers to the point where the world had to be wiped and the NPC factions had to be disabled.Mining and industry is a massive bordem simulator and nobody is interested in buying from other players and prefer to make everything for themselves, playing as a merchant or an industry corperation/faction is simply not practical or fun unless you are on an enforced roleplay server. Worth noting that any servers that encourage/enforce roleplay are empty 99% of the timeThe developers and the a large amount of the players would rather reject and/or insult people who are critical of the game then take on these criticisms or make valid arguments as to why they are wrong.The games popularity and people actually playing the game are on a downward trend.Resources in survival multiplayer are far to common, there is no reason to leave your home system to mine, you can quite literaly survive and thrive on only a fraction of the resources avaliable in a single system, keep in mind that the ""spawnpoint galaxy"" alone has hundreds of systems like this.Information collection in open systems is far to scarce, the game gives you almost no ability to find other players to interact with.The one galaxy where you spawn alone is huge, which is both a blessing and a curse if you are playing on multiplayer. The game does not have enough players on servers to justify having such a large area to play in, with the amount of players on servers, the universe feels extrememly empty, especialy coupled with the fact that the universe itself has very little features with actual meaning.The universe you play in is bleak, boring and is almost completely empty. There is not much to explore or see. The only fun to be had in multiplayer is interaction with other players.Engine is eternaly locked in single threaded java as the lead developer is not willing to make any changes to the engine he created.The developers refuse to give players the oppurtunity to fix their own game, several talented java coders exist within the community but Schine rejects any suggestion of allowing these coders to make ""unoficial patches"" or mods.It should be noted that this review is based on more than 4 years of playing this game, having 500 hours in the steam client and thousands more in the standalone launcher, I have participated in almost every form of gameplay this game has to offer in addition to seeing many faces of this community come and go for reasons similar to my own, namely Mushroom Fleet, ToasterBorst and Comr4de.EDIT: I should have probably mentioned that while this game is in alpha development stage (which is a common excuse used by the roaming white knights to justify the games problems) this game has been in this alpha stage for 6 years, only recently have they decided to completely replace the old system mechanics which they had not even finished developing for the old one prior to this change.Also, the ""its an alpha game"" excuse becomes null and void when you compare it to other games in the same development stage as StarMade that actually work, see the quote at the top of this page."
