76561198054582889,Recommended,244770,26538928,"Posted: 11 November, 2016",all,DWM,"I played this game many hours, and I mean, I played it a lot. I'm more than a year active on some servers now, and I had a lot of fun.But like every song, the fun comes slowly to an end, and it starts to bore me.When I played this game for the first time, it was the incredible possibilities that kept me hooked. Spaceships, small and big, stations... and thanks to the rail function and logic, I was busy for a while..I met many players, and build a lot. And we showed off with what we had.But there is an interesting problem. Starmade isn't an RTS where you can spawn ships like cheap cannon fodder for war. You put almost your soul in these ships, which makes you more reserved to battle against friend or foe. Especially big ships... which takes a lot of time and resources to build them... It isn't far-fetched to see some  players raged-quit after losing their capital ship....The planets are... not really interesting. Sometimes you find even an 'artefact'  on these planets and  they are very rare. But not good enough to explore the galaxy. After a while you will see them nothing more than as something to mine, and a message that you killed a lot of people (which is in my opinion still a dead planet if there's nothing that moves on it than only yourself) if you blow them up, shrugs you off  like something not important....They're too small to be important and interesting, and still too big, because they can often lag your computer...The only interesting thing in the galaxy are the players and even that starts to bore you, because the action is rare between them. You have some guys that like to grieve you, but that looks almost like the pinnacle of the game, really....Battle between ships is a problem too. Forget the small ships. They are just fodder. A battle is almost based on 1:1  system. The ship with the most (shield and shield regen) blocks (almost) wins. When you fight with two Battleships against one Titan, you can count on it that one battleship will be heavy damaged, probably will be destroyed...You can simply forget the epic battle with many small ships (5000-15000 blocks) against a Capital ship of almost 4 million blocks with an heavy shield. Even if you came with 80 (that will probably lags the server),  you will lose them, just because they have not enough fire-power and  a weak shield.  (the 10 second punishment time after losing your shield is just deadly for small ships)But that is just about ships and battle.What I really miss in this game is the reward system.  Why would I explore the galaxy if there are no hidden treasure or secrets? Why would I battle if there are no special rewards?It would be a dream, If I found a blueprint of a special block on a planet  that would give me an upperhand in battles, like a stronger shield block or power block and weapon. Or special ores for these blocks. Just think about that.They are working on AI factions now.... They just put new players in the field, but without an interesting reward system, they will bore you fast enough....I don't think the programmers will read this review, but you get the idea.Still, is this game worth it? I say yes, it's a great game for your creative dreams. But I can only hope that they don't forget an really good reward system then a cloud of blocks from pirates..., otherwise it will only be a building game...."
76561197978546580,Recommended,244770,18476450,"Posted: 14 October, 2015",all,lukwan,"I started off loving Starmade...then we broke up. Now I spend time thinking about maybe giving it a another shot. I got into the game just after the big graphical re-boot having played Minecraft for years and checking out every voxel based, procedurally generated game I could find. I trolled Greenlight and found many wanna be contenders but Starmade impressed me with it's vision of what it wants to be. Like any relationship we fall in love with what could be, an ideal, sometimes a projection we place onto the other. I am love with what Starmade is trying to be, but has not yet become.I lost interest for awhile when the docking update changed how turrets and ships dock. I was having a blast using the quirky old system to make a wide range of ships. The new system looks great and will solve many foibles and allow for a great variety of new designs. Just like with the Minecraft updates I got to enjoy a new game play each time Notch added something. Starmade is developing much the same way but because of it's own ambition each major update is quite disruptive. I have seen other early access wallow aimlessly, become abandoned or run off the rails in development. Starmade is doing none of these things. The danger, as I see it, is that Starmade may have trouble fulfilling it's grand ambitions.Yes this game has a learning curve and I had fun riding that curve. This is the gold-standard for a complex game. If the learning is fun; success, if it is tedious; go play a game more suited to your short attention-span. A simple game is easy to learn and may become boring. A game with depth and possibilities is going take time to master but will remain engaging.In it's current state (shipyards just released) Starmade is a very solid, playable early access game. There is a smattering of enemies to keep you improving your ship designs. There is no story arc yet but the ship-building is very polished. The Devs have built a proper foundation for an amazing game. It remains to be seen if they can build an engaging experience onto their ground-breaking mechanics while maintaining balance.Look elsewhere for the hate, I'm going to tell you what I love.>Design matters. Where you put modules and how you protect your ship will really make a difference. Lots of room for tactics, countermeasures and cool systems. My first death in the game was a suicide. I designed anti-personnel pulsers in the airlock. Two passes and you are still ok, the third pass: you're dead. (You can come in, look around and leave safely or... linger and die.) I died testing the system and laughed my♥♥♥♥♥off.>If you can dream it up you can build it. The first major ship I built was a salvage craft. I designed it to rescue shipwrecks. It was big and turned like a pig but fast and survivable. (I used it for daring rescue of a huge ship that got cored by pirates. It was an epic mission that left massive chucks missing from the old Flat-top but both vessels made it home intact. WooHoo)One of my favorites is the Tholian Enervater: a spider-themed hunter-killer. By design this craft can pursue a small fighter, slow it down using (web) multiple tractor beams (locking it in the crosshairs), rob it of power using (venom) an electro-mcGuffin ray and finally kill it. The theme of the spider worked both visually and tactically. Very Cool, good job Devs.I decided to make a Whale-ship that could swallow a pirate-craft whole and then eat it. It worked just as I had hoped. (Unfortunately collisions are unavoidable)I have stealth designs, a 'Tuttle-craft' for repairs, a surveyer/scout, a carrier/salvager, a mining ship with a huge beam.  = ]  Racing has just been introduced so now 'Tuning' will be a part of designing an efficient racer.> Hey, it's fun to fly too. Never mind the awesome build mode with simple and powerful symmetry & mirroring to reduce keystrokes... this is a very good space cockpit interface. Starmade features a huge number of elements introduced by previous space games but incorporates them well, often getting better results than its predecessors. It may not have the graphical grandeur of Klingon Academy but the systems controls are simple and easy to use in combat. After narrowly escaping from battle and badly damaged, I was able to reconfigure my systems and piece two non-functional weapons into one cobbled together mess of a gun (without going into build-mode). As I limped home I felt like Scotty, under an instrument panel with sparks flying, griping to the ham fisted captain who got us into this mess in the first place (oh, wait...that's me).Dog fighting is still a bit slow and not very dynamic with the current AI. I hope for more variation in their tactics besides ""Send more guys"".  Multiplayer servers often have custom pirates so there is lots of room for variety.>Potential. There's that dirty word again. With human crews for opponents in a more populated (by NPCs) world this game could be epic on a level beyond the average tired space-shooter game. It already has nailed the galactic map, shop-economy, building, flight control, and optimization. Read the developer's blog (Bench) to get a look at what is to come. The game updates every couple of weeks with new features, bug fixes and optimizations.>Powerful logic-driven systems. Think wireless redstone only more stable. Weapons with aux effects, electronic countermeasures and transporters. Shipyards to generate virtual designs and a BluePrint for your builds to save, share, upload, download & modify, all seamlessly.>Friendliest PvP I have ever seen in a game.>This game is better and more polished in it's Alpha state than many 'finished' releases I have bought.>Going into 2016 there has been a cargo and thruster update offering realistic, mass based acceleration and more thruster dynamics with user customizable settings. Fleets are set to add another dimension to the Meta-game. Slabs are expanding build-potential.For the earth bound crowd who complain that game is broken: try to find it in your imagination that this game is still in the chrysalis phase. The grub's body is utterly dissolved in the cocoon before it can be reborn into a butterfly.Early access is just that... if you don't get that stop bothering the developers and go play something with Zombies.For the Developers: Schine on."
