76561198043574057,Recommended,244770,19092301,"Posted: 15 November, 2015",all,Fynnarius,"First things first...  in my opinion) this game is amazing, but far away from being flawless:Starmade is a voxel based sandbox game in space. A game where the player is able to build massive objects like a fully functional(!) Deathstar or a Viper from Battlestar Galactica or anything else one can think of. The only limit is ones own imagination. But thats not all. There are plenty of different things to explore, like space stations or ancient ruins on planets. Or you can just adventure out into deep space, to find asteroid fields to mine. And as an nice addition, the map is gigantic!That said, getting into the game can be a bit rough, because the tutorial, while it is very helpful and offers plenty explanations about everything in the game, is buggy as hell and pretty boring (although, that opinion can differ from person to person) .The controls are easy to learn, but a bit, well, I would say underwhelming. You cant decide how fast you fly. It is either maximum thrust or nothing. Also, the menu system is far from perfection and very confusing at first.And please dont even speak about the AI-quality.So, what is it, that makes me love the game, as much as I do?Well, here´s a list:- Starmade is very configurable through some easy to understand config. data- Huge fleet battles are possible if your rig is strong enough, that said, Starmade runs pretty smooth overall. Even on low end systems.- Dogfighting is super fun.- Weapon systems are pretty in depth- Starmade looks astonishing beautiful, if you`re into that kind of voxel based textures.- Multiplayer runs very smooth, as long as your ping is manageable-And most important, the overall mixture of building, fighting, exploring, mining and more building is just funThat said, I DONT recommend this game, if you plan on playing Starmade purely for the singleplayer experience. because, the lack of (good) AI and nice NPC ship designs is kinda meh.On a server with dozens of people on the other hand, this game is amazing. (Or even a small one, with just you and your two or three best friends). You can even upload ships or stations you've built in singleplay onto the server.Personal rating: 8,5/10"
,Recommended,244770,13299225,"Posted: 9 December, 2014",all,chronosws,"The good:- A tutorial - as in there actually is one and it's moderately useful- Various texture packs built in to the client so it looks less Minecraft-like- You can build *massive* ships and there is a decent selection of utlity modulesThe middling:- OK build tools - far better than Minecraft, maybe worse than Space Engineers- The star systems are basically all the same - pick any one and you can find every resources you need, no reason to explore- There are NPC enemies, and they will pester you, but don't expect to be challenged by cleverness.  Tenacity perhaps...The bad:- The crafting interface.  Yes it has a filter to search, but no categorization.  Browsing a small list is painful.- The UI elements.  Ok, this is early access, some of it is likely developer art.  Recommend these guys go look at Space Engineers for a better example of UI.- The flight model.  Flight games *scream* for a joystick and rudder system - this system only supports one controller at a time so unless your stick does everything, it comes out to be much less useful.  Using a keyboard and mouse to fly anywhere near a planet is basically an exercise in frustration - get a gamepad at the minimum for when you step inside a ship.This game is like Minecraft in space, but without so much grinding trying to find resources (they are in fact very easy to get once you build a salvage ship - you will spend more time waiting for the resources to process than actually acquiring them.)  If you like *building* things, you will enjoy this game.  If you like *fighting* things, your enjoyment will probably be short-lived.  If you like *exploring*, you're enjoyment will also be short-lived.But it's still Early Access, so give it some time.  It will no doubt improve (just see how far Space Engineers has come along.)"
