,Recommended,244770,24531564,"Posted: 25 July, 2016",all,Bricarus,"As a space sandbox, Starmade is one of the most optimized games I've seen in a long time. It doesn't take much to run the game at 60 FPS, considering that I got 150 on an old laptop. Plus the whole ""no loading screens"" is true, and it makes the game even more fun.Would I recommend it before Space Engineers? No, not at all. I wouldn't even recommend Space Enginners if you wanted to get this game. Both Starmade and SE are completely different styles of space sandboxes, and it's all personal preferance on which one is better.If you want to be more creative with your ships, make them easier to run, and have tons of feature while spending little time building them, I'd get Starmade. If you're more into building ships around combat that can survive well, still very creative in design but a little more limited, have ingame coding with C++, and hundreds of mods to boost gameplay, I'd get Space Engineers.But enough about comparing the two, let's get back to Starmade. In this game, building is very similar to that of a mix of Minecraft and Space Engineers; you can build single blocks, lines, planes, or large blocks, but all the blocks are smaller than your character. This allows building to go fast, and allows you to put detail in small sections like corridors and bridges without making the ship huge. Stated earlier, the optimization in Starmade is great, and you can easily get 60 FPS. AI is also present in the forms of crew mates and faction members, as well as enemies and shop keepers, making the game more fun in single player. And, just to rap this up, being creative is super easy, since many design options are available to use.If I missed anything, it's probably because I haven't played in so long. Things change over time."
