76561198050995758,Recommended,244770,25321509,"Posted: 3 September, 2016",all,yo tiga now,"It is hard for me to find anything bad to say about this game. The building system is intuitive, the physics in space feel believable, the building possibilities are endless, unless you wanted to build a perfectly spherical ship, and it is pretty satisfying when you destroy a pirate/player station. Your experiences in the game will vary from singleplayer to multiplayer in the following ways...SingleplayerAs long as you are a person that enjoys building for its own sake, you will have a good time building in peace at a leisurely pace. You may be attacked by pirates randomly, however, so do not be surprised by seeing the red arrows on your screen, and possibly getting sniped.Building and testing out ship designs that could be anything from a starfighter to a cargo ship, a mining ship to dreadnought, a beautiful piece of functioning art to a hideous agglomeration of nonesense. Only you can see it, unless you import it to a multiplayer server. To make it even better, now you can make entire fleets of ships!With your warships, destroy all the pirate stations you come across, or tradestations.Eventually the NPC system will be expanded, giving you new things to interact with, or destroy. Currently, the only non-ship NPCs are Space-Spider-Things (hostile), traders (Passive but creepy), and a mercenary type NPC you can hire (also creepy).Singleplayer is like a space loneliness simulator with an ominous wind sound in the background, but if your ship or station is decorated well, it doesn't feel as bad.MultiplayerJust like every game, some servers are full of PVP players, and others are role-playing PVE servers. My experience with both have been largely positive, however, as I was rarely attacked in the beginning by more settled characters. Until I had a large ship and homestation, the only characters that were solely KOS were other people who just started. Once you have a base and ship you put a lot of work into, you become more reluctant to be openly hostile to everyone. When everyone hates you in a server, life becomes very stressful.When you get the chance to see other characters' ships and stations, it is interesting to see the different designs people come up with. I have seen fleets of ships from Star Wars, Mass Effect, Halo, Star Trek, Eve, and countless other series. There is nothing like seeing a Star Destroyer fighting a Borg Cube. In my favorite server I built a space strip club that other players could dock at for a visit.Eventually you will fight another player, whether you attacked them, they attacked you, or it was a challenge in chat, you will have to approach it in a completely different way than battles with pirates. You will see different combinations of weapons and uses of logic systems you had never thought of.Showing off the complexity of your work is really fun, but mastering the logic system takes time. I still know very little about the logic systems.The universe is so vast that you might not see your neighbors unless one of you is actively seeking the other out. Some people might not like the emptiness of space and the distances between everything, but that is just how space is.The number of griefers in multiplayer is fairly low from what I've seen. Griefers usually want quick gratification, something this game does not offer, and will try to steal from established players. If you build a few systems away from spawn, they probably won't make it. Have some turrets ready just in case.Get ready to mine a lot and build yourself a proper factory. It is too expensive to buy everything from the shops.This game is fantastic and is still getting better. The Devs are incredibly talented and hardworking, just not as vocal about what they are working on as some others, for example, the Rust Devs, who post about everything they work on. The Starmade Devs are always working on something and it makes a difference. The game used to run really slow for me, but now my frame rate is excellent. I'm excited to see what they will add in the near future. To sum everything up, I recommend buying this game if you like both building and Sci-Fi, and also have the patience to get into this game. You could also try the free demo to determine if you are willing to pay for the future of the game. I'm done."
