76561198105424287,Not Recommended,244770,24773408,"Posted: 8 August, 2016",all,Goip,"Note: Just tried to play again today, and I couldn't connect to any servers because 'runtime encryption error'. So, that should tell you at least something about what a struggle it is.Now, my opinion on Early Access games comes with a warning. I'm not gonna ♥♥♥♥♥foot around. I'm going to review the game AS IS, and I'm going to completely disregard everything that is promised or expected for this game. When you buy an Early Access game you don't buy a promise for a good game, you buy the game as it is in it's current state. I'm going to tell you what you'll get for your money.Now, I didn't spend an overly large amount of time on this game. Not at all, in fact. But it doesn't need an overly large amount of playtime to see what this game is.This game is not an exploration game. This is not a massively multiplayer game. This is a ship-builder. You build ships. Maybe you make a factory to get ship components, or maybe you salvage components from the pirate ships that just kind of fly around and generally do nothing. But really, you build ships. Don't get me wrong, that's really fun, and playing with the logic system and all the guns is really great. Heck, I even had a good time figuring out how to power my massive freaking behemoth destroyer. But all you really do is build ships.Occasionally it's possible to fly around and screw with other players, which is a kick, and there's the pirate stations to destroy, but the lack of other content in this game is grating. It has a few really good systems, but there is almost nothing besides those. Flying around in a huge ship shaped like a phallus is great and all, but there's next to nothing to do but just that. Fly around.There are NPCs in StarMade, but really NPC describes them for almost exactly what they are. Non-player characters. Nothing more, nothing less. There are pirates, but they're just computers in some outdated drone ships. Pirate stations have no pirate NPCs to fight, just ships and defenses. There're shops, but they're entirely player operated and stocked, basically. All of this just adds to the lack of depth.The description promises epic fleet battles, but really there is none of that unless you're a really good organizer or can find a group that regularly arranges those. The biggest battle I've ever been in was with one aggravating player and 2 of his friends. There's not really anything to fight over anyway. (Unless you really value hunks of rock floating in space.)There's a mountainous learning curve to all this, and although I managed to conquer it, some won't.It's tough, no doubt about it, but mostly worth it if you manage to figure it out. Most of the fun of this game is learning, but once you exhaust that, it's just shipbuilding and flying from there.Now, I've so far not mentioned any of the glitches this game boasts. I'll list these here, but don't cry to me about how 'the game is Early Access and it's going to have SOME bugs, come on', because Jesus H. Christ on a bike, there is a lot more than 'some bugs'. It is because of this and the fact that there is NO GAURANTEE that the game will have them fixed that I am going to gripe about them. They've persisted this long, and I know, the developer fixes bugs. But the lack of additional content I've seen added to this game gives me this sinking feeling that there is not really going to be anything major done to this game. (Please, oh PLEASE developer, prove me wrong.)Launching the game for the first time is a battle. If it doesn't work, there's a mile's long list of the things that could have caused it. Java out of date? Oh, you have the x64 AND x32 versions of Java? Have a slight headache? Good luck trying to get it to cooperate. Really. The worst part is, once you solve one problem there is almost ALWAYS going to be another. If you hate a game crashing, then you'll really hate StarMade, because this game has crashes GALORE. They happen almost randomly, which is the most frustrating thing when playing. The best part? There's no gaurantee that that thing you did to launch the game last time is gonna work again.TL;DRThe game is buggy as hell, the dev 'works' on the game, but not really in any significant capacity, and the game has about as much depth as a puddle of water on a hot summer day. In it's current state, I do not reccomend it. Maybe  wait around, see if the dev really does anything, and if they do, THEN cash in. But until then, I can't say this game is worth 15$.But hey, if you like building ships and rigging super complex logic boards, then give it a try. The demo IS free, after all.But don't say I didn't warn you.Edit: Yes, I know you don't have to buy the game. That's why I'm posting the review here and not on the demo page. Also, the launcher just dropped yesterday and it fixes a big complaint of mine.P.S.If you're thinking about posting a negative review, apparently that is looked down upon, as I have recieved multiple messages (Yes, messages, not comments) on how my opinion was♥♥♥♥♥♥and I shouldn't have posted this. If you have read this and are thinking of messaging me, please refrain from doing so, as that is a step BEYOND the line of suggestion."
