,Not Recommended,244770,13416021,"Posted: 17 December, 2014",all,Pompadour Excellante,"UPDATE - 6/25/17 - This game has not changed much, even 3 years later. I am quite disappointed to see many of the same problems still persist, including a few new ones such as rubber banding near planets. I am changing my review to not suggest this game as the developers don't seem that interested in improving the game or fixing simple problems. Heck, even the base player model has not changed even after years of development. That is very sad to see. I see the general population has not grown much either, undoubtedly due to the aformentioned problems. This game is nearly unplayable due to these kinds of problems and I will no longer be following it.With the advent of the modern voxel adventure title, StarMade may slip past most gamers radar as just another Minecraftesque space themed pretender. Unfortunately for them, they're missing out on a gold mine of entertainment. I haven't been 'addicted' to a game for a long time now, and StarMade has definitely flipped the fun switch for me. If you're a fan of voxel games, it's definitely worth checking out, and if you're a fan of space exploration, you'd be an idiot not to.StarMade has many elements that make the game fun; the building, the vast reaches of unexplored space to cruise in, the challenge of facing unknown enemies, making alliances, resource gathering to gain power, and far more. All of these elements gel very well into what many people are referring to as an EVE experience. Though I don't like comparing StarMade to EVE, there are many resemblances to it, which isn't necessarily a bad thing. The game is just really fun, especially if you have goals and friends to play with. Once you get a firm grasp on how to build ships (or just figure out how to search up blueprints on line and gather resources in-game to build them) the game really starts to kick off, as you'll find yourself making different classes, arming your planets/stations, and really just being a force in the galaxy. The only negative I see is the building itself, it can be a challenge to master the concept of building up an entire ship from a single block, but the mechanics are simple enough that most should be able to figure it out. Additionally, adjusting to movement and gravity mechanics can also be a bit of a challenge for the unexperienced. There is a lot of work that still needs to be done with adjusting the UI, adding a proper soundtrack, and various other elements that make a game complete, but it's still in early access after all and you really can't complain for the amount of content you're actually getting at the moment.Considering this game is still in development, I am quite eager to see what else awaits us in the future of the great black yonder."
