76561198121876323,Recommended,244770,14253273,"Posted: 30 January, 2015",all,bloodbornangel,"Hello eveyone.Now I've played quite a few early access games in my time on steam (Years of gaming that aren't all on this account.) and I've seen some terrible alpha's that probably will never go into beta or release for real.StarMade is a beautiful exeption. (be ready for semi-long rant)I jumped into the game thinking it would just be some half-baked copy of Minecraft. I was so wrong. Many people who are familiar with Minecraft will wonder why that game isn't as advanced as StarMade has become. Building you're own ship that flies, uses complex energy algorithms that contribute to everything from shields, to weapons, and many other sci-fi mechanics for spaceships is so satisfying! You can make the most amazing ships! It is a little more difficult to build then minecrafts style, but the game is no where near finished and it will probably be updated to be easier later on.And that's another great point. The game is no where near finished.That might not sound great, but with all the content you already have hours of enjoyment. I spent most my time building a mid-sized ship and that took me 20 hours! I see people with ships 3x, 5x, even 10x larger then mine. The system is so much more advanced then redstone and the massive amount of technology that you can create is astounding and will keep you tinkering for hours. If you want to build more then a basic ship you'll have to look at the sites wiki because energy production and storage have some pretty complex rules but most of it will be explained in the tutorial. The game generated structers are amazing as well. Screw Hexxit and other Minecraft dungeon mods. The pirate stations are deadly and great challanges, and the space stations you can discover floating around are awe-inspiring. You can even generate your own. Planets and Stars are still a little buggy, but the physics system is solid so far. Gravity works pretty well. (Though the Mass-to-Gravity ratio seems strange.)Since I've been praising the game I'll give you a little more about the cons.The HUD is a little strange. Kinda bare bones in my opinion. There's a lot of helpful information but it could be better. Although the Navigation system is pretty good, there is no way to save coordinates as far as I know. (Unless you write them down yourself.) The radar/map thing you have isn't very helpful.. you have some dots that might be something close by.. but up or down or wherever you can't really tell. It is suppose to be updated soon. The AI isn't that developed yet. You can make an AI for your ship but its honestly pretty stupid and doesn't always work. I hear it is suppose to be able to fly your ship and stuff later on in development though. You can still use it for autoturrets but it can go rouge every once in a while. Pirate stations are OP on the other hand. They can take a massive amount of damage to their shields and some of their turrets do crazy amounts of damage. I had shields that very few other people on the server could take down easily, I nearly got my core destroyed in two shots from a pirate station.Planet shapes are also a real bi*!#. They are 3D pentagons as far as I remember at the moment. Maybe hexagons. Jumping around corners and having your gravity reorient is really disorientating. Also big ships can get stuck on them if you don't have a high thrust. So taking off is really difficult if you've got a 1500 mass battleship. It's usually better to make a small mining ship and dock it to you're bigger ship. Leaving the big one in orbit.The size of the game is really overwhelming too. Like.. you thought minecraft is big... It took me 20 minutes to get to the edge of the core systems.. I was still had half my galaxy to go before reaching the outer rim. Jump drives shorten the time if you have enough power to charge them a lot.Anyways I'm done ranting on about the game. Right now the Demo is the same as the full Alpha that you can purchase now. It will only be free for a limited time though. So try it out and see for yourself. Most people will help newbies if you ask nicely.I'm off to build a spacestation and conquer a star system. ;)"
