,Not Recommended,244770,24016992,"Posted: 2 July, 2016",all,[L.M.B 2nd S.L] Spooker West-468,"So, this game is EXTREMELY fun to play with a couple friends.As a terrible designer and builder I can safely say that my role in StarMade is to steal unclaimed ships.So, my first experience was rather interesting.I went mining with my friends and we gathered some ores over the course of an hour and made millions off of it, which was an amazing start. We started to build a ship of our own, but we decided others' ships were much better and we'd work much better stealing and running. So we did just that at the spawn.Over the next week, the Spaghetti faction got a reputation for stealing ships on SystemHack. So that was fun. It got to the point where our mothership was tiny compared to our biggest ship, but we still called it Spaghettimother since our big miner was NOT a residential ship.However we lost interest after people learned to claim their ships, and with our owned ships we got bored of fighting pirates and exploring the same small pentagon-faced planets.All in all, this game is fun for progressing and quick empire-building. But once you've done the main stuff, there's no fun in just flying around the same few planets. Of course, professional builders would say otherwise. I've seen some amazing builds, ranging from tiny X-Wings and TIE Fighters to giant flying buses, huge warp rings and cresent-shaped fighters that could house a large village of people inside it.For a player who wants to just have fun exploring and fighting, this game gets boring quite quickly with the fact I have to rebuild and repair my ship block by block after every fight if my shields go down. I'm sure others think differently, but I think more exploration methods would really make StarMade better.Oh, also, travelling is a bloody awful burden. Took me an hour to get to the edge of the galaxy. Went and had a good meal while I was waiting. Warping doesn't help much either."
76561198115473609,Not Recommended,244770,25390220,"Posted: 6 September, 2016",all,Charles_Fitzgerald,"Short Version:There is not too much to do other than build. If you absolutely love building sci-fi stuff, then pick up the demo and try it out. If you're not a fan of sinking hours and hours of your life into trying to make that perfect starship, then avoid the game for a while and then check back later to see if anything was added that makes you want to play the game.Very Long Version:Having been playing this game for a while, I can say that I would not recommend it in its current state unless you love to build.Expanding on that idea of loving to build, Starmade has one of the best set of tools for building whatever the fudge you want in this game. The not horribly demanding placement of blocks in order for a ship to work allows for a fair bit of flexibility in making a ship that works alright, all you really have to do is place the more finicky things in lines and the rest everywhere else. The inclusion of the advanced build mode features accessible by holding down lcontrol allow one to define symmetry planes, place hundreds of blocks at once, copy n' paste and more! Various systems such as rails and logic also give a player the ability to make various functioning mechanisms as simple as an elevator or password-protected door or as complicated as Space Monopoly (yes, someone did do that). It's even possible to create a basic OS on your ships to execute commands from a console in order to lock down, flash red alerts, undock drones, and whatever else you would want to do!The main issue, however, is that the game is very hard to get into. The tutorials are confusing and not necessarily up to date, the UI is not very intuitive, and some game mechanics are very abstract.The main case of those issues is the current power system. The way power works has a weird, non-intuitive pattern of construction in order to work effectively. One has to create groupings with an emphasis of covering large dimensions to generate more power per block, or else end up placing way more blocks than needed and making a severely underpowered ship compared to its cost. This forces design choices centering around large power crosses or large lines of power and is overall not very interesting to create. Hopefully this will be fixed in the power overhaul that the devs have annouced will take place.Another problem with the game is the lack of survival gameplay. The devs certainly are working on it, and that's great, one can certainly see that with the addition of basic NPC Faction generation, but there still is not much to do. There's no real reason to explore after seeing all the different ships and stations because everything that is randomly generated is pretty much the same old stuff. There's nothing like nebulae or ion storms that could provide navigational challenge or special gaseous resources, crashed ships with flight data or blueprints, or dangerous pirate territory stacked with loot (pirates now don't count because the danger level of pirates is pretty much constant wherever anyone goes, and there's no real reason to raid them) that spawns in the universe.Nothing is there to push a player or provide danger in the universe of Starmade either. There's no hunger or oxygen mechanics to drive one to gather resources, and the act of gathering resources to build stuff is super boring, amounting only to pointing your ship at an asteroid, turning on your radar jammer to negate any and all danger, and holding down right-click for a while.Manufacturing, industry, and trade is also far from entertaining. Crafting stuff is just typing in what you want to make, looking at the recipie, and putting the stuff in the factory. If you're a more advanced player, then you can just skip that last step and let your automated sorting system do it for you. No player will actually buy something another player makes because it's way more efficent just to mine it yourself through the boring process of holding down right-click on an asteroid until it disappears. Being a merchant is further frustrated by NPC factions only buying from a player in small amounts. Communication with these factions to convince them to buy more is also impossible, simply because they are in such a basic state.There's not much on the diplomacy front, either. There's no unique territory, and you probably will start out in a system filled with everything you will ever possibly need if you plan right, so there's no reason to invade anyone else or negotiate with anyone else for resources. Trading is, as stated earlier, impossible because everyone is completely self-sufficient.With a lack of strong content in terms of exploration, manufacturing, interaction and survival, I cannot recommend the game in its current state to others unless you absolutely love building. If you do like to build, then there are exceptional tools available that provide endless possibilites.Though, please do note that the game is completely free in its early access stages. Just click the ""download demo"" button to get the full version. You may as well try it out to judge it for yourself, and if you don't like it stop by after a while. The devs are extremely active and tell the community what they're working on every single week! Many of these issues are scheduled to be fixed some time in the future, it's just that Starmade is still getting onto its feet."
